{{Italic title}}
The '''''American School Board Journal''''' is a monthly [[trade magazine]] on school administration established in 1891 by the United States [[National School Boards Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Delpit shines a light on education in the inner-city |url=http://www.subr.edu/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/408 |accessdate=7 April 2013 |newspaper=Southern University |date=1 March 2013}}</ref>
== Scope == [[File:Heaton School Board Journal April 1922 Cover.png|thumb|Illustration of how placement of school pupils into classes changed after widespread use of [[IQ test]]s, from cover of April 1922, '''American School Board Journal'''.]]
The focus of the ''American School Board Journal'' is on the challenges of [[K–12 (education)|K-12]] [[State school|public schools]] and topics related to school leadership, governance, management, policy making, and student achievement.
== Magna Awards == The ''American School Board Journal'' organizes the "Magna Awards" which is an annual program to showcase [[school district]]s and projects in the United States which are examples of innovation and excellence in school governance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Magna Awards |url=http://www.asbj.com/magna |publisher=National School Boards Association |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> The program was started in 1995 by the magazine with an objective to highlight [[Board of education|school boards]] that improve educational programs by taking remarkable steps.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cullotta |first=Karen Ann |title=1st Year Results In National Award For Choice School |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-04-19/news/0004190244_1_new-school-pupil-magna-awards |accessdate=7 April 2013 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Currently, the Magna Awards program is co-sponsored by the National School Boards Association and [[Sodexo]].
Nominees are separated into three categories based on the size of their school districts: enrollment under 5,000, from 5,000-20,000, and over 20,000. In each category, there is one grand prize winner, five additional awards and five honorable mentions. The criteria of judging include the involvement of the school board, the success of the projects, the ability to replicate in other school districts, and the advancement of student learning.<ref name="whatis">{{cite web |title=What is Magna? |url=http://www.asbj.com/MainMenuCategory/Supplements/MagnaAwards/WhatisMagna.aspx |publisher=National School Boards Association |accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref>
== Awards and recognition == The ''American School Board Journal'' received the following awards: * Two articles from the magazine were finalists of the ''[[National Magazine Awards]]'' in 1980 and 1984 in the categories of "Specialized Journalism" and "Public Service" respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=National Magazine Awards: Winners and Finalists |url=http://www.magazine.org/asme/national-magazine-awards/winners-finalists |publisher=American Society of Magazine Editors |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> * The 2001 "Golden Lamp Award" in adult publication from the [[Association of Educational Publishers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2001 Golden Lamp Award Winners |url=http://aepweb.org/aepweb/index.php/awards/aep-awards/finalists-a-winners/archives/golden-lamp-award-winners/508-2001-golden-lamp-winners.html |publisher=Association of Educational Publishers |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> * The [[Education Writers Association]]'s ''National Awards for Education Reporting'' in multiple years.<ref>{{cite web |title=EWA Announces Winners of National Reporting Contest |url=http://www.ewa.org/site/PageServer?pagename=contest_winners |publisher=Education Writers Association |accessdate=6 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502161955/http://www.ewa.org/site/PageServer?pagename=contest_winners |archive-date=2013-05-02 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
