'''Marion Freschl''' (née Szekely) (January 16, 1896 - November 23, 1984, New York City) was an American [[opera]]tic [[contralto]] and [[voice teacher]] of Hungarian descent. A member of the voice faculties at the [[Curtis Institute of Music]] and the [[Juilliard School]], she taught several highly successful singers, including [[Marian Anderson]], [[Joan La Barbara]], [[Brenda Lewis]], [[Joanna Simon (mezzo-soprano)|Joanna Simon]], [[Shirley Verrett]], and [[Camilla Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/26/obituaries/marion-freschl.html|title=Marion Freschl|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 26, 1984}}</ref>
Both Freschl and her brother, [[baritone]] and voice teacher [[Rudolph Szekely]], were trained at the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music]] and began their careers as resident artists at the [[Hungarian State Opera House]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Music Business and Monkey Business|author=Doug McGuire|pages=42–43|publisher=AuthorHouse|year=2010}}</ref> She went on to sing leading roles at opera houses in Germany, Austria and Scandinavia before immigrating to the United States in 1941. In the 1920s she was active with the [[Berlin State Opera]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=New releases|work=[[The Phonograph Monthly Review]]|volume=3|year=1928|page=254}}</ref>
